<p>I have </p>  <p><code>f(x) = sin(x) - 1 + cos(x)</code></p>  <p>I want to know for what values there will be catastrophic cancellation in the interval [<code>0</code>, <code>pi/4</code>] for single precision floating point ie. [1 sign][8 exponent][23 mantissa].</p>  <p>I know that when <code>x</code> is near <code>pi/4</code> then <code>cos(x)</code> and <code>sin(x)</code> will add to, close to, <code>1</code> and that will be a problem when subtracting <code>1</code>.</p>  <p>How do I figure out how close to <code>pi/4</code> I need to get before I start losing single precision digits?</p>  <p>I know that if two positive normalized floating point machine numbers are <code>x</code> and <code>y</code>, then <code>2^-p &lt;= 1 - y/x &lt; 2^-q</code> then at most <code>p</code> and at least <code>q</code> significant binary bits are lost in computing <code>x-y</code>.  </p>